EDA on Loan dataset from Prosper

This is an exploration of loan dataset that was downloaded from Prosper. Prosper is a marketplace lending platform where individuals can invest or borrow money. It allows people to invest $25 or more fr a given loan listing.

Dimensions of the loan dataset:

## [1] 113937     81

The loan dataset has 113,937 loans along with 81 variables for each loan. The variables specify the attributes of the loan and well as the individual requesting the loan.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 113937 observations and 81 variables. Only 15 variables out of the original 81 are considered of interest for this analysis.

  • Term: There are 3 values for Terms (12,36, and 60). 36 month seems to be most common.

  • LoanStatus_mod: Has values of Bad Loan, Completed, Current and Past Due (<30 days). Cancelled loans are removed.

  • ProsperScore: Ranges from 1-11. Although, according to the documentation, it should only be 1-10.

  • CreditScoreRangeLower: Ranges from about 500 to 900. Majority of individuals have credit score between 650 and 750. Median value is 699.

  • IncomeRange: Values include ‘Not displayed’, ‘Not employed’, ‘$0’, ranges of values from $1 to $100,000, with increments of $25,000, and anything equal to or larger than $100,000. Most income seem to be in the ranges ‘$25,000-49,999’ and $50,000-74,999.

  • DebtToIncomeRatio: IQR range is 0.14 - 0.32. There are some ratios higher than 1, but those are considered outliers.

  • TotalInquiries: For most cases, most inquiries seem to be between 0 to 6. Mean number of inquiries is 5.58.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features of interest are as follows: “LoanStatus”, “Term”,“BorrowerAPR”, “CreditScoreRangeLower”, “ProsperScore”, “IncomeRange”, “TotalInquiries”,“DelinquenciesLast7Years”, “DebtToIncomeRatio”

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Other features that might help are: “BorrowerAPR”, “ProsperRating..Alpha.”, “EmploymentStatus”, “EmploymentStatusDuration”, “IsBorrowerHomeowner”, etc.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Yes. I created LoanStatus_mod with consolidated bad-loan values.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Removed LoanStatus=“Cancelled”. The objective of this analysis is to study what differentiates good loan from bad loan. If the loan was cancelled, it did not contribute to the objective.

Reordered the levels for IncomeRange to make them appear in the plots in desired order.

IQR range of Credit Scores for Bad Loans are lower compared to that of other Loan Statuses.

Number of Delinquencies in past 7 years does not seem to determine if the loan will be ‘bad’.

Overall, there doesn’t seem to be any relationship between Inquiries in last 6 months and Debt to income ratio

Explore relationship between Income Range and Loan Status

Loans with higher Income Range have smaller rate of Bad-Loans.

Next, we study the same relationship but without ‘Current’ loan status.

After excluding ‘current’ loan status, for income range ‘$100,000+’, about 25% are classified as Bad Loan. Comparing that to income range ‘$1-$25,000’, only about 35% of loans are classified as Bad loans.

Explore relationship between Income Range and Debt to Income Ratio

Loans with low income have debt to income ratio more spread out (with some exceeding 10.0). Whereas, Loans with higher income consistently have very low debt to income ratio.

Pairwise graphs of variables among variables that are not of main interest:

Among variables that are not of Interest, BorrowerAPR vs. Estimated Return, and Estimated Return vs. EstimatedLoss have highest correlation. I guess it makes sense that loans with higher APR have higher Estimated Returns. I expected Borrower APR to have high negative relation with EstimatedLoss, but that doesn’t seem to be the case.

Multivariate Plots Section

Explore relationship between ProsperScore and Loan Status, grouped by credit score ranges:

Credit scores 800 to 900 seem to have very less proportion of Bad loans for higher Prosper Scores. But for lower Prosper scores in the same credit range, the proportion of Bad loans are comparable to other Credit Score ranges. This tells us that just looking at the Credit Score might not be enough to determine if the loan will be good or bad.

Higher Income ranges and higher Prosper Scores have less proportion of Bad Loans, compared to lower Income Ranges and Lower Prosper Scores.

Explore relationship between Credit Score and mean Income Ranges, for each Loan Status type:

In general, mean credit scores for people with bad loans are lower compared to that for other groups. Surprisingly, overall credit scores for unemployed people is fairly high. For them, mean credit score do not seem to be good indicator their Loan Status.

For employed people, Income range and mean Credit Score seems to be good indicator of Loan Status. For example, people with Income Range of $1-24k with ‘Bad’ loan status have average Credit score of ~650. Whereas people in same Income Range with ‘Completed’ Loan Status have mean Credit Score of ~670. This trend is seen for all Income Ranges.

Explore relationships of Credit Scores, Income Range, and InquiriesLast6Months to Loan Status:

When we add InquiriesLast6Months into Credit Score and Income Range, it shows, on average, there are more Inquiries in Last 6 Months for Bad Loans, compared to other loan types.

Completed loans have lower number of Inquiries in Last 6 Months, but they are still larger than Current loans (esp. in lower Credit Score ranges). This might be because of the fact that completed loans includes past loans where investors were more willing to take larger risks (and therefore reaped larger rewards). But the investors for current loans are less willing to take risks.

Study relationship between Income Range and Loan Status, by Income-Vertifiable.

Non-verifiable Income group seems to have equal percentage of Bad Loans for all income ranges. Therefore, for Non-verifiable group, Income Range does not seem to be good inidcator of Loan Status.

Explore relationship between Income Ranges and Debt to income Ratio, for each Loan Status type:

Loan Status values are uniformly spread out across range of Debt to income Ratio values, for different Income Range values.

Explore relationship between Debt to income Ratio and Inquiries in last 6 months, for each Loan Status type:

Looking at the mean Inquiries in Last 6 Months for different levels of Debt to Income Ratio, it is hard to read the chart because there is too much fluctuation over a short range.

So, we smooth the chart by grouping Debt to Income ratio into increments of .5, and taking the mean of InquiriesLast6Months. The smoothed plot shows that Bad Loans have higher Inquiries in past 6 months compared to any other Loan Types.

In the lower range of DebtToIncomeRatio (0-2.5), it is interesting to see than Bad Loans deviate from Good Loans by a huge margin in terms of Inquiries in Last 6 Months. For DebtToIncomeRatio above 2.5, Loan Status values do not seem deviate a lot from each other.

Another interesting observation is that alonst all Current loans have DebtToIncomeRatio below 1, peaking around .7. What can be the reason for this? Maybe this the threshold where risk and return are optimal?

Next, we attempt to facet the graph by Income Range:

In general # of Inquiries are higher for Bad Loans compared to other Loan Statuses, for all income Ranges and Debt to Income ratio ranges.

For loans with Income Range of $1k to $25k, Not employed and Not displayed, # of inquiries are significantly higher for Bad Loans compared to Completed Loans.

For Income range $25k or higher, # of inquiries are similar for all loan statuses.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the

Loan Status (whether a loan will be Defaulted or not) seems to tbe highly related to Prosper Score, Credit Score, Income Ranges and Inquiries within last 6 months.

Income Range and Credit Score strengthened each other. Debt to Income Ratio and Inquiries within last 6 months also strengthened each other.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the
strengths and limitations of your model.

I was expecting that the loans with higher Debt to Income Ratio will have more instances of Bad Debt. But that did not seem to be the case.

For unemployed people, mean credit score do not seem to be good indicator their Loan Status. But for employed poeple, it seems to be good indicator.

The fact that loans with Income Range ‘Not employed’ and ‘Not displayed’ does not have any ‘Current’ loan status might mean that loan is no longer offered if the individual is unemployed.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This plot shows how Credit Scores, Income Range, and InquiriesLast6Months relates to Loan Status. Bad Loans have higher mean number of Inquiries compared to the good ones, especially at lower Credit Score ranges. As the Credit Score increases, the difference becomes less and less obvious.

Plot Two

Description Two

This plot shows that Debt to Income Ratio is not really a good indicator of Loan Status. This shows that people with higher debt are not necessarily more likely to default on their loans.

Plot Three

Description Three

This plot shows that Income Range and Credit Scores are good indicator of Loan Status, but only for employed individuals.

Individuals with lower income seem to have lower Credit Scores in general, and among them, the individuals with bad loans seem to have lower credit scores than the completed/current loans.

The mean credit score for ‘current’ loans are very high. This might be because people have started avoiding loan listing that have attributes which could potentially lead to the loan being defaulted - in other words, investors taking less risks with the loans.

Reflection

This exploration was primarily focused on identifying attributes that distinguished between Completed loan and Bad Loans. Current loans were also studied.

Variables such as Prosper Score, Income Range, Credit Scores, and Inquiries made in Last 6 Months were all related to Loan Status in varying degrees. There variables are pretty good indicators to distinguish Bad loans from completed and current loans. It is also seen that perhaps the investors of current loans are more risk-averse than the investors for past completed & bad loans. Investors for current loans seem to be seeking out loans with higher credit scores and less number of Inquiries in Past 6 Months.

More work needs to be done to identify the strategies to generate most expected return for an investor. I believe valriables such as Borrower APR, Estimated Return, Listing Category, time since loan origination, and other attributes about the member can help investors maximize their returns.
